<li>Reznek, Lawrie, 1987, <em>The Nature of Disease</em>, London:
Routledge &amp; Kegan Paul.</li>

<li>Robinson, Daniel N, 1996, <em>Wild Beasts and Idle Humours: The
Insanity Defense from Antiquity to the Present</em>, Cambridge, MA:
Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;The Insanity Defense as a
History of Mental Disorder&rdquo;, in Fulford et al. 2013:
18&ndash;36. doi:10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199579563.013.0003</li>

<li>Rose, Nikolas, 2009, &ldquo;Normality and Pathology in a
Biomedical Age&rdquo;, <em>Sociological Review</em>, 57 (Supplement
2): 66&ndash;83. doi:10.1111/j.1467-954X.2010.0188</li>

<li>Rose, Nikolas S. and Joelle M. Abi-Rached, 2013, <em>Neuro: The
New Brain Sciences and the Management of the Mind</em>, Princeton, NJ:
Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Roskies, Adina L., 2003, &ldquo;Are Ethical Judgments
Intrinsically Motivational? Lessons from &lsquo;Acquired
Sociopathy&rsquo;&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Psychology</em>, 16(1):
51&ndash;66. doi:10.1080/0951508032000067743</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, &ldquo;Neuroethics beyond Genethics.
Despite the Overlap between the Ethics of Neuroscience and Genetics,
There Are Important Areas Where the Two Diverge&rdquo;, <em>EMBO
Reports</em>, 8(S1): S52&ndash;S56. doi:10.1038/sj.embor.7401009</li>

<li>Russo, Jasna and Angela Sweeney, 2016, <em>Searching for a Rose
Garden Challenging Psychiatry, Fostering Mad Studies</em>, Wyastone
Leys, UK: PCCS Books.</li>

<li>Russell, Denise, 1995, <em>Women, Madness, and Medicine</em>,
Cambridge: Polity Press.</li>

<li>Sadler, John Z., 2005, <em>Values and Psychiatric Diagnosis</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/med/9780198526377.001.1</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Values in Psychiatric
Diagnosis and Classification&rdquo;, in Fulford et al. 2013:
753&ndash;778. doi:10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199579563.013.0045</li>

<li>Sadler, John Z., K. W. M. Fulford, and C. W. Van Staden (eds.),
2015, <em>The Oxford Handbook of Psychiatric Ethics</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.
doi:10.1093/oxfordhb/9780198732365.001.0001</li>

<li>Samuels, Richard, 2009, &ldquo;Delusion as a Natural Kind&rdquo;,
in Broome, and Bortolotti 2009: 49&ndash;80.
doi:10.1093/med/9780199238033.003.0004</li>

<li>Sass, Louis Arnorsson, 2001, &ldquo;Self and World in
Schizophrenia: Three Classic Approaches&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy,
Psychiatry, &amp; Psychology</em>, 8(4): 251&ndash;270.
doi:10.1353/ppp.2002.0026</li>

<li>Sass, Louis, Josef Parnas, and Dan Zahavi, 2011,
&ldquo;Phenomenological Psychopathology and Schizophrenia:
Contemporary Approaches and Misunderstandings&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy,
Psychiatry, &amp; Psychology</em>, 18(1): 1&ndash;23.
doi:10.1353/ppp.2011.0008</li>

<li>Savulescu, Julian, Ruud ter Meulen, and Guy Kahane (eds.), 2011,
<em>Enhancing Human Capacities</em>, Oxford: Blackwell Publishing.
doi:10.1002/9781444393552</li>

<li>Schaffner, Kenneth F. 2012. &ldquo;A Philosophical Overview of the
Problems of Validity for Psychiatric Disorders&rdquo;, in Kenneth S.
Kendler and Josef Parnas (eds.), <em>Philosophical Issues in
Psychiatry II: Nosology</em>. Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
169&ndash;189.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, <em>Behaving: What&rsquo;s Genetic,
What&rsquo;s Not, and Why Should We Care?</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195171402.001.0001</li>

<li>Schramme, Thomas (ed), 2014, <em>Being Amoral: Psychopathy and
Moral Incapacity</em>, Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</li>

<li>Schwartz, Peter H., 2008, &ldquo;Risk and Disease&rdquo;,
<em>Perspectives in Biology and Medicine</em>, 51(3): 320&ndash;334.
doi:10.1353/pbm.0.0027</li>

<li>Scull, Andrew, 2009, <em>Hysteria: The Biography</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Shorter, Edward, 2006, &ldquo;Hysteria and Catatonia as Motor
Disorders in Historical Context&rdquo;, <em>History of
Psychiatry</em>, 17(4): 461&ndash;468.
doi:10.1177/0957154X06073012</li>

<li>Singh, Ilina, Walter P. Sinnott-Armstrong, and Julian Savulescu
(eds.), 2013, <em>Bioprediction, Biomarkers, and Bad Behavior:
Scientific, Legal, and Ethical Challenges</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199844180.001.0001</li>

<li>Sinnott-Armstrong, Walter (ed.), 2008, <em>Moral Psychology,
volume 3: The Neuroscience of Morality: Emotion, Brain Disorders, and
Development</em>, Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</li>

<li>Spitzer, Manfred and Friedrich A. Uehlein, 1992,
&ldquo;Phenomenology and Psychiatry&rdquo;, in Manfred Spitzer,
Friedrich Uehlein, Michael A. Schwartz, and Christoph Mundt (eds.),
<em>Phenomenology, Language &amp; Schizophrenia</em>, New York:
Springer-Verlag, pp. 35&ndash;45. doi:10.1007/978-1-4613-9329-0_3</li>

<li>Stanghellini, Giovanni, 2004, <em>Disembodied Spirits and
Deanimated Bodies: The Psychopathology of Common Sense</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press. doi:10.1093/med/9780198520894.001.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, <em>Lost in Dialogue: Anthropology,
Psychopathology, and Care</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Stegenga, Jacob, 2008, <em>Care and Cure: An Introduction to
Philosophy of Medicine</em>, Chicago: University of Chicago
Press.</li>

<li>Stein, Dan J., Katharine A. Phillips, Derek Bolton, K. W. M.
Fulford, John Z. Sadler, and Kenneth S. Kendler, 2010, &ldquo;What is
a Mental/Psychiatric Disorder? From DSM-IV to DSM-V&rdquo;,
<em>Psychological Medicine</em>, 40(11): 1759&ndash;1765.
doi:10.1017/S0033291709992261</li>

<li>Stone, Tony and Andrew W. Young, 2007, &ldquo;Delusions and Brain
Injury: The Philosophy and Psychology of Belief&rdquo;, <em>Mind &amp;
Language</em>, 12(3&ndash;4): 327&ndash;364.
doi:10.1111/j.1468-0017.1997.tb00077.x</li>

<li>Summers, Jesse S., 2015, &ldquo;What is Wrong with
Addiction&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy, Psychiatry, &amp; Psychology</em>,
22(1): 25&ndash;40. doi:10.1353/ppp.2015.0011</li>

<li>Summers, Jesse S., Sinnott-Armstrong, Walter, 2019, <em>Clean
Hands: Philosophical Lessons from Scrupulosity</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Sulik, Gayle A., 2011, &ldquo;Our Diagnoses, Our Selves: The Rise
of the Technoscientific Illness Identity&rdquo;, <em>Sociology
Compass</em>, 5(6): 4463&ndash;477.
doi:10.1111/j.1751-9020.211.00374.x</li>

<li>Svenaeus, Fredrik, 2013, &ldquo;Anorexia Nervosa and the Body
Uncanny: A Phenomenological Approach&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy,
Psychiatry, &amp; Psychology</em>, 20(1):
81&ndash;91.muse.jhu.edy/article/511263</li>

<li>Szalai, Judit, 2016, &ldquo;Agency and Mental States in
Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy, Psychiatry,
&amp; Psychology</em>, 23(1): 47&ndash;59.
doi:10.1353/ppp.2016.0001</li>

<li>Szmukler, George, 2016, &ldquo;Coercion in Psychiatric Treatment
and Its Justifications&rdquo;, in Moseley and Gala 2016:
125&ndash;146.</li>

<li>Szmukler, George and John Dawson, 2011, &ldquo;Reducing
Discrimination in Mental Health Law&mdash;The &lsquo;Fusion&rsquo; of
Incapacity and Mental Health Legislation&rdquo;, in Kallert, Mezzich,
and Monahan 2011: 97&ndash;119. doi:10.1002/9780470978573.ch7</li>

<li>Tabb, Kathryn, 2015, &ldquo;Psychiatric Progress and the
Assumption of Diagnostic Discrimination&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy of
Science</em>, 82(5): 1047&ndash;1058. doi:10.1086/683439</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2019, &ldquo;Philosophy of Psychiatry after
Diagnostic Kinds&rdquo;, <em>Synthese</em>, 196(6): 2177&ndash;2195.
doi.10.1007/s11229-017-1659-6</li>

<li>Tan, Jacinta O. A., Tony Hope, and Anne Stewart, 2003,
&ldquo;Anorexia Nervosa and Personal Identity: The Accounts of
