doi:10.1007/978-94-017-9765-8_3</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;Natural Kinds, Psychiatric
Classification and the History of the DSM&rdquo;, <em>History of
Psychiatry</em>, 27(4): 406&ndash;424.
doi:10.1177%2F0957154X16656580</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021, <em>Philosophy of Psychiatry</em>,
Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. doi:10.1017/9781108588485</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;Biological Essentialism,
Projectable Human Kinds, and Psychiatric Classification&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy of Science</em>, 89(5): 1155&ndash;1165.
doi:10.1017/psa.2022.64</li>

<li>United Nations, 2006, <em>Convention on the Rights of Persons with
Disabilities (CRPD)</em>, Department of Economic and Social Affairs.
 [<a href="https://www.un.org/development/desa/disabilities/convention-on-the-rights-of-persons-with-disabilities.html" target="other">United Nations 2006 available online</a>]</li>
 
<li>Ussher, Jane M., 2011, <em>The Madness of Women: Myth and
Experience</em>, (Women and Psychology), New York: Routledge.</li>

<li>Varela, Francisco J., Evan Thompson, and Eleanor Rosch, 1991,
<em>The Embodied Mind: Cognitive Science and Human Experience</em>,
Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.</li>

<li>Varga, Somogy, 2015, <em>Naturalism, Interpretation, and Mental
